window.docContents[54].resolve({"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/Cardinality-of-product-sets-and-the-doubling-constant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--Cardinality-of-product-sets-and-the-doubling-constant--Submultiplicativity-of-the-Product-Set":{"contents":"(Submultiplicativity of the product set.) For finite subsets  of a group,\n\nAdditively, ; the additive statement is Finset.card_add_le.\n\nThe product set  is the image of  under the multiplication map\n. The cardinality of the image of a finite product under any binary operation\nis at most the product of the cardinalities (Finset.card_image₂_le), since the map can only\nidentify pairs, never create new values. Specialising the operation to multiplication gives the\nbound.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Additive and Combinatorial Number Theory\u0009Cardinality of product sets and the doubling constant","header":"10.1.1. Submultiplicativity of the Product Set","id":"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/Cardinality-of-product-sets-and-the-doubling-constant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--Cardinality-of-product-sets-and-the-doubling-constant--Submultiplicativity-of-the-Product-Set"},"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Cyclotomic-extensions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Cyclotomic-extensions":{"contents":"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory","header":"3.12. Cyclotomic extensions","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Cyclotomic-extensions/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Cyclotomic-extensions"},"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/The-discriminant-and-the-different-ideal/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--The-discriminant-and-the-different-ideal--The-Discriminant-of-a-Number-Field":{"contents":"The discriminant  of a number field  is the determinant of the trace\nform () in an integral basis  of\n ():\n\nIt is independent of the chosen integral basis (two integral bases differ by a matrix in\n, whose determinant is ), and its absolute value measures\nthe arithmetic complexity of .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory\u0009The discriminant and the different ideal","header":"3.5.1. The Discriminant of a Number Field","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/The-discriminant-and-the-different-ideal/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--The-discriminant-and-the-different-ideal--The-Discriminant-of-a-Number-Field"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-p-adic-numbers-and-integers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-p-adic-numbers-and-integers":{"contents":"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces","header":"5.3. The p-adic numbers and integers","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/The-p-adic-numbers-and-integers/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--The-p-adic-numbers-and-integers"}});